ID Code: 2nd point on page; can't read writing. - oversample

COMMENTS: Virginia Gibbs (USFS) and I spent a few minutes in the area after the survey protocol had ended, trying to determine whether any GWWA were present. One male GWWA was finally found and was observed at length (singing, calling, and aggressively responding to conspecific playback) near the survey location. This area has been surveyed in past years (by Chris?) but I don't know the coordinates of the location(s) surveyed. One male was on territory here in 2014. The total extent of suitable habitat within the entire length of the powerline right-of-way is unknown.

ID Code: Survey 2 - same location as 2014 Survey #10 - oversample
COMMENTS: There does not appear to be enough shrubby habitat at this location to support GWWA. The property is composed primarily of open field (little to no shrub layer) surrounded by mature forest.

ID Code: Survey 3 - same location as 2014 Survey #11 - oversample
COMMENTS: The Vermivora individual heard during CPB minute 6 was singing a typical BWWA song. In 2014, an individual that appeared to be a phenotypically pure GWWA was on territory in this area and alternated between GWWA and BWWA song. The bird singing during the 2015 survey was not located and, thus, his ID was not confirmed. In 2015, a female GWWA was observed carrying food near the survey location after the survey had ended (w/ photographic documentation). I did not attempt to locate a nest but the female's behavior indicated that there was a nest present. There were 2 male GWWA on territory here in 2014.

ID Code: Survey 4 - same approx location as 2014 Survey #1 - oversample
COMMENTS: There was one male on territory in this area in 2014. It's possible that the 2015 survey was run too late in the morning, although the male on territory in 2014 would often sing into early afternoon. I was not able to return to the area to conduct a second survey.

ID Code: Survey 5 - same location as 2014 Survey #8 - oversample
COMMENTS: The area being managed for GWWA habitat is fairly small. Landowners are open to further management of the habitat; Patrick Farrell has been working with them.

Patrick Farrell has surveyed this property in the past but I don't know the precise location(s) of his surveys. One male GWWA was on territory in 2014. A male Brewster's Warbler was observed in an area adjacent to the GWWA's territory over the course of one day in 2014.

ID Code: Survey 7 - same location as 2014 Survey #3 - oversample
COMMENTS: Could not confirm that the bird observed during mobbing PB was a second male GWWA. "Unofficial" surveys by Steve Semanchuk and Liz Skiles indicate that, historically, there likely has been more than one male GWWA in this area. The area is dominated by mature forest with a few shrubby patches and mowed paths--i.e., not typical GWWA habitat. A GWWA nest w/ nestlings was found near the survey location in 2014.

ID Code: Survey 8 - same location as 2014 Survey #4 - oversample
COMMENTS: In 2014, there were 2 male GWWA on territory at this location. In 2015, it appeared that the area was again being defended by 2 different males. A GWWA nest w/ nestlings was found near the survey location in 2014. Cattle were present throughout the area in 2014 but were not observed in 2015.
